Add 300ml cold salted @water{300%ml} to a #medium pot{} with a tight-fitting lid.
Stir in the @rice{150%g} and bring to the boil.
Once boiling, lower the heat to medium, cover with the lid and cook for ~{10%minutes}.
Once cooked, remove the #pot{} from the heat.
Keep covered for ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped into small pieces).
Peel and grate the @garlic{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).
Halve the @chilli{½}(halved lengthways, deseeded and finely chopped) (double for 4p).
Trim the @pak choi{1}(trimmed and halved lengthways).
Trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed and halved lengthways), then chop widthways into ½ cm pieces.

Place a #large pan{} over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.
Once the pan is very hot, sear the @Irish beef strips{250%g} until cooked through, shifting as they colour, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat and its packaging. Meat is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

Once cooked, remove from the pan and set aside.

Return the pan to medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil.
Add the carrot, onion, garlic and chopped chilli (use less if you don't like spice).
Cook until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.
Add the pak choi and cook until wilted, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add the beef to the pan along with the @ketjap manis{2%sachets} and @soy sauce{1%sachet}.
Mix everything together and allow to warm through.
Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.
Remove the pan from the heat and stir the @honey{1%sachet} through the sauce.
Trim the @scallion{2}(trimmed and thinly sliced).

> TIP: Add a splash of water if the sauce is too dry.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and share between bowls.
Top with the beef strips and saucy veg.
Garnish with a sprinkling of sliced scallion.